{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592397"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:13:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:13:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15229"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15229"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.17,0.09,0.06,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65141"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7920"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15229"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50577"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"2171"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21645"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65141"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EColorectal cancer is one of the five most common malignancies in Australia, the others being breast, lung, prostate and melanoma. There are a number of different screening methods for colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is not currently recommended in Australia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colonoscopy","Faecal immunochemical testing","Faecal occult blood testing","Flexible sigmoidoscopy","Stool DNA testing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn Australia, the National Bowel Cancer Screening Program primarily uses faecal immunochemical testing (FIT) as the initial screening tool for average-risk individuals aged 45-74 years. Understanding the available and recommended screening options is crucial for healthcare providers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStool DNA testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not currently recommended or available through Australia\u0027s national screening program, although it is available in some other countries. This test looks for altered DNA in cells shed from colorectal cancers and advanced adenomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal occult blood testing\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecal immunochemical testing\u003C/strong\u003E are both validated screening tools. FIT has largely replaced traditional guaiac-based FOBT due to its superior sensitivity and specificity for detecting human haemoglobin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E remains the gold standard diagnostic test and is used both as a screening tool in high-risk individuals and as a follow-up investigation for positive FIT results. It allows direct visualisation of the entire colon and immediate biopsy of suspicious lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible sigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E, while less commonly used in Australia, is still a recognised screening tool that examines the distal third of the colon. It may be appropriate in certain clinical scenarios, though it does not visualise the entire colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe choice of screening method depends on various factors including patient risk factors, preferences, and local availability. The current Australian guidelines emphasise FIT as the primary population screening tool, with colonoscopy reserved for high-risk individuals or investigation of positive FIT results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Faecal occult blood testing (FOBT) and faecal immunochemical testing (FIT) are the primary screening tools for colorectal cancer in average-risk individuals.","Colonoscopy is the gold standard diagnostic test for colorectal cancer and is used for both screening and surveillance.","Stool DNA testing is an emerging screening modality that detects genetic markers of colorectal cancer."],"references":["Kumar R, Lewis CR. Colon Cancer Screening. [Updated 2024 Sep 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559064/","Lin JS, Perdue LA, Henrikson NB, Bean SI, Blasi PR. Screening for Colorectal Cancer: Updated Evidence Report and Systematic Review for the US Preventive Services Task Force. JAMA. 2021 May 18;325(19):1978-1998. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.4417. Erratum in: JAMA. 2021 Jul 20;326(3):279. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.10417. PMID: 34003220.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50577"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15229"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50577"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T15:27:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T15:28:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7920"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65141"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self